<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/17134133-aomame"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1619719233i/17134133._UY100_CR12,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/17134133-aomame">Aomame*</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I loved the first three stories (the jaina who starves heself to death, the teyyan dancer and the sacred prostitute Rani). Sadly I found stories to be<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I loved the first three stories (the jaina who starves heself to death, the teyyan dancer and the sacred prostitute Rani). Sadly I found stories to become less and less engaging as the book moved on: to me, it was as if Dalrymple played his ace card at the very beginning. After that, reading became kinda tedious...<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
