<div id="review_1934373209" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1934373209" />
    <a title="Hazel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/613387-hazel"><img alt="Hazel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1351223887p2/613387.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1934373209?book_show_action=true">Apr 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hazel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hazel" href="/user/show/613387-hazel">Hazel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1934373209" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11954469627672633927">An interesting travel read about 9 religious pilgrims, each from different religions in India. It made me reflect on religion in general, how it can potentially have the power to transform someone, and help people experience life on a deeper level. On the flip side, it can also be strange and unusual, and push people to do odd things. Also it can divide people. I think it is always good to think critically, whatever your spiritual persuasions.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


